      en: `Original title: Câu chuyện Huệ Thanh có đại duyên lớn được gặp Sư Tam Vô khai thị
Narrator: Uyên, later named Huệ Thanh
Ten years of practice without clarity
Uyên was introduced to Buddhism in 2013. She diligently attended sermons, chanted sutras and mantras, freed captive animals, and participated in silent retreats. She once attempted to recite the Amitābha name three thousand times daily, believing that quantity would ensure rebirth in the Pure Land. Yet she still felt anger and frustration, arguing with her husband, and wondered whether her practice was correct: “How can I remain mindful when the six senses contact the six objects without getting caught? How can I master my thoughts?” After ten years she realised she had only switched from doing evil to doing good; she still practised in order to receive merit. She confessed she was lost in a tangled web until her sister (Huệ Tịnh) told her of Sư Tam Vô.
Questions from afar
Through a phone connection, she greeted the teacher and asked for instruction. He asked which path she followed. She said “Buddhism.” He asked: “What is Buddhism?” She replied that she read sutras and chanted the Amitābha name. He then asked: “If I am an unshaven monk and instruct you, do you trust me?” She answered yes, because she had long been searching for a teacher who could clearly show the way. He noted that her diligence—reading sutras, listening to sermons, chanting—is admirable but not liberating. “Do you know what ‘reciting the Buddha’s name’ (niệm Phật) means?” he asked.
She responded: “To remember the Buddha.” He probed: “Before you met your husband, could you remember him? If you have never met Amitābha, how can you remember him? Your daily repetition of ‘Namo Amitābha Buddha’ is just calling a name—you have not met him.” She faltered and begged for instruction. He explained that niệm is remembrance, and Phật refers to the enlightened nature within. To “recite the Buddha’s name” means to continually remember your own Buddha Nature and live from it, not to call a far‑off deity. He recited a long poem beginning with “A Di Đà Phật – How many call on Amitābha, yet they have never met him; they imagine the Pure Land is far away, not realising it is their own true nature. Recognise the deathless mind and you will find the Pure Land right here.” The poem explains that endless repetition of a name, without realising the mind’s nature, keeps one stuck in rebirth. One must stop wandering aimlessly and return to the “Old Home” within.
Transformation and family resistance
These words illuminated her mind. She realised she had been chanting mechanically and seeking externally. She told her husband she had found a true guide and longed to travel to meet him in person. Her family opposed, thinking she was being fooled. On the morning of her flight she tried to leave quietly, but her mother and siblings physically held her back, tearing her coat. She realised she lacked the merit to meet him. She remained at home, practising the teacher’s instructions: living consciously, fulfilling her roles as daughter, wife and mother. Gradually her family became harmonious. Later her husband, seeing her transformation, began listening to the teacher’s discourses and called him “Sư Cha” spontaneously during a session. Eventually the whole family became students, and she travelled to meet the teacher with them. Upon meeting in person, she bowed and asked for guidance. He treated her like a daughter, teaching her how to live rightly and see the inherent nature in daily activities.
`
